&gt;&gt; I unfortunatly DID spend 6 months at lvl 52 dieing multiple times to keep 52. Prehaps, you do not know what it feels like to see all your friends who you have grouped with since lvl 20 at lvl 60 and you are still 52 and thus unable to group with them in the high end game? prehaps when your 3 closest ingame friends take you on low lvl raids out of sympathy or.. when you go with them and unintentionally agro mobs due to your lvl and wipe them all out just because they wanted you to be with them. Prehaps you should try that.<br>
<br>
That was your *choice*, no one put a gun to your head and made you stay 52 to try for your epic. While I am sympathetic to anyone who loses grouping with their friends, that doesn't mitigate the fact that it was a choice on your part to do so and that does not give you special rights to looting that would never be considered in most other raid situations in pickup groups. Either stay 52, try for your epic, and bite the bullet with regards to your friends leveling past you, or bypass your epic (or live with the hope of the luck on a Kunark dragon) and level up and group with your friends.<br>
 <br>
&gt;&gt;What lvl are you sir?<br>
<br>
I am 52. Once I hit 51 I stopped going for experience at all, and all my experience is incidental to being in the KS group on a raid, helping someone get an item etc. I;ve been 51-52 for over 3 months, and since I got to 51 in 3 months, that will tell you that I easily could be 55+ by now if I wanted, but I *chose* to try for my epic. And yes I have had some friends go on, some join the resident uberguild, etc. And yes, it does suck to see the people I grouped with all the time in my 30s and 40s as high as 59 and doing things that I can't do, but again, that was my *choice* to do so just for a big flaming sword.<br>
<br>
&gt;&gt;Why is this bitter? this quest is after all supose to be &quot;Epic&quot;<br>
<br>
FA was a pre-Kunark quest. Just because the FD part of the quest can be done relatively easily, does not mean squat. The only reason you or anyone else would want the epic items moved to Kunark dragons only would be to 1) force more people to be interested in killing Kunark Dragons, 2) take your bitterness out on paladins lower than 52 just because you are upset that you tried so long and hard for your epic and are jealous of people that got lucky. I am sorry, but moving the epic loot to the Kunark dragons only is petty, unfair, and just plain stupid. And &quot;epic&quot; is relative. I remember in my first eq go around 2 years ago thinking of how &quot;epic&quot; the Soulfire seemed and how amazing the the planes armor was (not val, the stuff before val was put in) or how awesome rubicite was. Now that is a distant memory. verant has stated before that epics aren;t the &quot;be all end all&quot; weapon for a class, and as the next expansion comes out FD will fall even further behind the highest end weapons. It is a high level quest, with a great reward, but just because people call it &quot;epic&quot; doesn't mean that only people 55+ should have a shot at it.<br>
<br>
&gt;&gt;sorry i dont have the stomach to watch 20-60 people throw themselves at a mob and die while i watch not takeing any danger to myself whatso ever.<br>
<br>
Oh god, what danger? That some sprites on the screen might die? That someone might lose a fraction of a blue or exp after being rezzed? These people go there mainly for the chance at good items, some go for the experience, but most don't. If you want to RP and be all &quot;noble&quot; and &quot;chivalrous&quot; etc. fine, don't organize a raid, but if you don't have the &quot;stomach&quot; for that why do you ahve the &quot;stomach&quot; for some alt of yours to fight and your main to get the rewards? Apparently it is ok for your main to send in his or her littler brother to do all the dirty work and reap the rewards, but not for you to send in an army? <br>
<br>
&gt;&gt;rules should ALWAYS be stated before the raid commences if you do not like the rules then leave it is quite simple.<br>
<br>
Of course, but that wasn't the point of this discussion was it? The point was a discussion over the &quot;ethics&quot; of it in the EQ world. <br>
<br>
&gt;&gt;your second statement contradicts the first. Loot rules are stated by the raid leader and nobody else. if the paladins that have come on the raid do not agree to this then tough.. the rules are spoken before hand and like EVERYBODY else they have legs.. <br>
<br>
Like I said, this wasn't the issue we are talking about now is it? A leader could make a rule that they get all the loot and no one rolls for anything, and it is still possible to get a group of people together that just want to participate or get dragon practice, but that doesn't make it &quot;fair&quot; does it? And that is what we are talking about, what is &quot;fair&quot; versus &quot;unfair&quot;.<br>
<br>
&gt;&gt;personally i have found paladins to be more usefull on dragon raids then most clerics, paladins heal much m,uch faster and i always make sure that the cleric does not heal me if i need a heal i wait till im low enough and loh or stop attacking lose agro back off and heal myself that why i dont trouble the cleric with worrying about one of their tanks.. or i dont overrite any of their heals.<br>
<br>
Um, well, then you are in the minority then. Anyway, I don't remember ever being healed at a dragon raid anyway, the things die too quickly for anyone to need or get a heal most of the time. So maybe that 500 damage or more you might do before the dragon falls is useful, but is in no way more useful than a cleric adding 600+ hp and some AC to up to 10 people, allowing them to survive several more partially resisted AE blasts.<br>
<br>
<br>
&gt;that doesn't give that character the right to roll on epic class specific loot.<br>
<br>
&gt;&gt;i never said it did<br>
<br>
But that is what you are supporting explicitly.<br>
<br>
&gt;&gt;dragon loot is sold on your server? interesting.<br>
<br>
Of course it is. I play on The Rathe, a very very old server that only had its first ever server split a couple of months ago. Everyday in EC RBBs, CoFs, tons of low level dragon loot like Hiero crooks, etc., even Kunark class armor BP and Legs might be found for sale. Often dragon books, scales, etc. are also sold.<br>
<br>
&gt;&gt;i never said for one second that i had not got this agreed with specific raid leaders well before the actuall event. unless it is made blatently clear before the event took place i would never roll on a book. i have been on numerous dragon raids for nothing less than a pat on the back from the cleric who was too high lvl to help clear naggy so they could get to rage.<br>
<br>
Again you are skirting the main topic, what is &quot;ethical&quot; versus unethical, not what you have gotten a raid leader to agree to and thus forced every single other paladin on the raid to either agree to or not participate. That is why I said earlier to get the other paladins to agree. You are essentially &quot;cheating&quot; by working around the 52 level cap on the dragons and taking away that opportunity from a &lt;=52 paladin that may have stayed 52 while you leveled on and are fighting in ToV. By getting together with a raid leader and forcing this on the other participants you are not being &quot;ethical&quot; in my opinion. And we have all done stuff without getting rewards, so big deal. Its called being &quot;nice&quot; to try and help someone out.<br>
<br>
As I said, I feel it is different if you are organizing a raid for the purpose of getting a book. In that case you are the reason there is a raid at all, but when you are just another participant and get something like that cleared with the raid leader you are fucking over the other paladins. <br>
<br>
&gt;&gt;have you ever killed a kunark dragon sir?<br>
<br>
Other than the spawned Fay, no. So what? What's your point? That it is easier said than done? of course it is. But by not staying 52 or delevling you are getting the worse chances of getting your epic with the advantage of being able to level and do much more challenging things. <br>
